b.) Treat the year variable as ordinal, not nominal. More specifically, recode the variable as 0 (1960), 10 (1970), and 15 (1975). Note: This is different from the textbook suggestion of 0/1 indicator variables in Section 5.7.

Using dplyr, we recode the year variable as ordinal.

rawDummy <- rawDummy %>%
  mutate(year = ifelse(year == 1960, 0,
                       ifelse(year == 1970, 10,
                              ifelse(year == 1975, 15, year))))

d.) Plot the studentized (standardized) residuals vs.the fitted values (yb). Draw a normal probability plot (quantile plot) of the studentized (standardized) residuals. Which model assumptions appear to be violated? Explain.

First we plot the standardized residuals vs.the fitted values:

rawDummy <- rawDummy %>%
  mutate(std_res = rstandard(raw_interact), fitted_values = fitted(raw_interact))

gf_point(std_res ~ fitted_values, data=rawDummy) %>%
  gf_labs(x = "Fitted Values", y = "Standardized Residuals") %>%
  gf_hline(yintercept = c(-2,0,2), linetype=2)

It seems that the model assumption of constant variance for the errors is violated here. The spread of standardized residuals seemes to get much larger as the fitted values increase, which shows that the variance is non-constant.

Next we make the normal probability plot of the standardized residuals:

gf_qq(~ std_res, data=rawDummy, distribution=qnorm) %>%
  gf_qqline(distribution=qnorm)

This QQ-plot tests the model assumption that the errors are approximately normally distributed. The data fits the straight (normal) line relatively well, suggesting that a normal distribution isnt a bad approximation. Also, this graph seems to indicate one or two outliers which would contradict the assumption that all the observations have equal influence.

f.) Check basic model assumptions (linear relationship to Y, error variance, normality, influence, etc.)

To check linear relationship to Y, we use a standardized residuals vs.fitted values plot, and a scatterplot matrix with the predictor variables.

rawDummy <- rawDummy %>%
  mutate(std_res = rstandard(raw_logfit), fitted_values = fitted(raw_logfit))

gf_point(std_res ~ fitted_values, data=rawDummy) %>%
  gf_labs(x = "Fitted Values", y = "Standardized Residuals") %>%
  gf_hline(yintercept = c(-2,0,2), linetype=2)

ggpairs(rawData[, 2:7])

From the graph of the standardized residuals vs.fitted values we can see that the linear model is a reasonable assumption. Also, from the majority of the predictor variables it seems that there is a linear relationship to the response variable, so the linear model form assumption holds in this case.

We use a standardized residuals vs.fitted values plot to check the error variance assumption:

rawDummy <- rawDummy %>%
  mutate(std_res = rstandard(raw_logfit), fitted_values = fitted(raw_logfit))

gf_point(std_res ~ fitted_values, data=rawDummy) %>%
  gf_labs(x = "Fitted Values", y = "Standardized Residuals") %>%
  gf_hline(yintercept = c(-2,0,2), linetype=2)

The constant variance assumption seems to hold here as the spread around the horizontal line at 0 is constant over all the fitted values.

We use a QQ-Plot as before to check for normality of the errors:

gf_qq(~ std_res, data=rawDummy, distribution=qnorm) %>%
  gf_qqline(distribution=qnorm)

The QQ-Plot shows that the errors fit the normal distribution well, as the data lies mostly along the straight (normal) line.

To test whether the observations have equal influence, we use a graph of Cooks distance:

In order to test whether there is an overall effect from X1, X2, X3 on Y, we use an F-Test and we test the hypotheses: \(\begin{aligned}H_0: \beta_1 = \beta_2 = \beta_3 = 0 \ vs. \ H_A:\beta_i \neq 0\end{aligned}\) (for i = 1, 2, 3).

We use the anova function in R to compare the full model with the model under the null hypothesis where all the coefficients for the slops equal zero:

raw_fit_x1x2x3_FM <- lm(y ~ x1 + x2 + x3, data = rawDummy)
raw_fit_x1x2x3_RM <- lm(y ~ 1, data = rawDummy)
anova(raw_fit_x1x2x3_RM, raw_fit_x1x2x3_FM)
## Analysis of Variance Table

## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

From the F-test, the p-value is very small so we are can reject the null hypothesis that all the slope coefficients are zero. We conclude that there is a statistically significant overall effect from x1, x2, x3.

h.) Test whether the effects of X1, X2, X3 remain unchanged over time. Specify the hypothesis to be tested, the test used and your conclusions at the 5% significance level.

We test the hypotheis that the the effects of x1, x2, x4 remain unchanged over time by testing the null hypothesis that all the coefficients of the interaction terms are zero. We perform an F-test using a full vs.reduced model as before.

raw_fit_year_interact_FM <- lm(y ~ x1 + x2 + x3 + region2 + region3 + region4 + year + (year*x1) + (year*x2) + (year*x3), data = rawDummy)

2.) Modified from Exercises 5.7

Three types of fertilizer are to be tested to see which one yields more corn crop. Forty similar plots of land were available for testing purposes. The 40 plots are divided at random into four groups, 10 plots in each group. Fertilizer 1 was applied to each of the 10 corn plots in Group 1. Similarly, Fertilizers 2 and 3 were applied to the plots in Groups 2 and 3, respectively. The corn plants in Group 4 were not given any fertilizer; it will serve as the control group. Table 5.17 gives the corn yield yij for each of the 40 plots.

fertilizerData <- read.delim("http://statistics.uchicago.edu/~collins/data/RABE5/P158.txt")
head(fertilizerData)
##   Yield Fertilizer
## 1    31          1
## 2    34          1
## 3    34          1
## 4    34          1
## 5    43          1
## 6    35          1

a.) Create three indicator variables, F1, F2, F3, one for each of the three fertilizer groups (to compare against control)

We create indicator variables using the dummies package in R:

fertilizerDummy <- dummy.data.frame(fertilizerData, names=c("Fertilizer"))
fertilizerDummy <- mutate(fertilizerDummy, Fertilizer = fertilizerData$Fertilizer)
colnames(fertilizerDummy) <- c("Yield", "F1", "F2", "F3", "Control", "Fertilizer")

b.) Fit the model yij = 0 + 1Fi1 + 2Fi2 + 3Fi3 + eij .

We fit the following linear model in R:

fertilizerfit = lm(Yield~F1+F2+F3, data = fertilizerDummy)

c.) Test the hypothesis that none of the three types of fertilizer has an effect on corn crops. Specify the hypothesis to be tested, the test used, and your conclusions at the 5% significance level.

The null hypothesis is that all the slope coefficients equal zero, and the alternative hypothesis is that at least one of the fertilizer has an effect on corn crops: \(\begin{aligned}H_0: \mu_1 = \mu_2 = \mu_3 = 0 \ vs. \ H_A:\mu_i \neq 0\end{aligned}\) (for i = 1, 2, 3).

We use an F-Test in R:

glance(fertilizerfit)[-c(7:10)]
##   r.squared adj.r.squared    sigma statistic     p.value df df.residual
## 1 0.3000662     0.2417384 4.847107  5.144479 0.004604797  4          36

The value of the F-statistic is 5.14 and we have a p-value of 0.0046 which is less than our significance level of 0.05. The conclusion is that we can reject the null hypothesis and say that at least one of the fertilizer groups has a statistically significant effect on corn crops compared to the control group.

d.) Test the hypothesis that the three types of fertilizer have equal effects on corn crop. Specify the hypothesis to be tested, the test used and your conclusions at the 5% significance level.

The null hypothesis is that all the slope coefficients are equal, versus the alternative hypothesis that at least two of them are not equal.
\(\begin{aligned}H_0: \mu_1 = \mu_2 = \mu_3 \ vs. \ H_A:\mu_i \neq \mu_j\end{aligned}\) (for i,j = 1, 2, 3).

We use an F-Test with a reduced model vs.the full model:

fertilizerfit_FM <- fertilizerfit
fertilizerfit_RM <- lm(Yield ~ I(F1 + F2 + F3), data = fertilizerDummy)
anova(fertilizerfit_RM, fertilizerfit_FM)
## Analysis of Variance Table
## 
## Model 1: Yield ~ I(F1 + F2 + F3)
## Model 2: Yield ~ F1 + F2 + F3
##   Res.Df    RSS Df Sum of Sq      F  Pr(>F)  
## 1     38 1088.4                              
## 2     36  845.8  2     242.6 5.1629 0.01068 *
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

The value of the F-statistic is 5.16 and the p-value is 0.01 which is less than 0.05. At the 5% significance level, we would conclude that there is some difference between the effects of the fertilizer groups.

e.) Irrespective of the results in (d), test whether there is a common effect of fertilizer, call it F , relative to control.

We assume that the effects of the different groups are equal, and this effect if \(\mu_F\). We use the same reduced model that we had in part (d) and we use the lm function in R to use a t-test for the hypothesis that this coefficient is statistically different from zero: \(\begin{aligned}H_0: \mu_F = 0 \ vs. \ H_A:\mu_F \neq 0\end{aligned}\)

fertilizerfit_RM <- lm(Yield ~ I(F1 + F2 + F3), data = fertilizerDummy)
tidy(fertilizerfit_RM)
##              term estimate std.error statistic      p.value
## 1     (Intercept)     29.8  1.692398  17.60815 7.206804e-20
## 2 I(F1 + F2 + F3)      4.0  1.954213   2.04686 4.763348e-02

The t-statistic is 2.047 and the p-value is 0.0476 for \(\mu_F = 0\). Testing at the 5% significance level, we reject the null hypothesis because the p-value = 0.0476 is less than 0.05. Assuming that there is a common effect of fertilizer, we reject the null hypothesis that it has no effect and we conclude that there is some non-zero common effect.

4.) Exercise 5.6 PARTS a-f

The price of a car is thought to depend on the horsepower of the engine and the country where the car is made. The variable Country has four categories: USA, Japan, Germany, and Others. To include the variable Country in a regression equation, three indicator variables are created, one for USA, another for Japan, and the third for Germany. In addition, there are three interaction variables between horsepower and each of the three Country categories. Some regression outputs when fitting three models to the data is shown in Table 5.16 (for those of you who do not have the new version of the textbook, Table 5.16 is on the last page of this homework). The usual regression assumptions hold.

carData <- read.delim("http://statistics.uchicago.edu/~collins/data/RABE5/P155b.txt")
head(carData)
##             Car Country      Y Horsepower
## 1 Acura Integra   Japan 12.100        130
## 2  Eagle Summit     USA  6.949         92
## 3   Ford Escort     USA  7.976         88
## 4  Ford Festiva   Other  6.620         63

a.) Compute the correlation coefficient between the price and the horsepower.

carData$Horsepower <- as.numeric(carData$Horsepower)

## [1] 0.8611619

b.) What is the least squares estimated price of an American car with a 100 horsepower engine?

Using model 2 we can use the formula \(\hat{y_0} = \hat{\beta_0} + \hat{\beta_{1}}x_i + \hat{\beta_{2}}x_j = -4.117 + (0.174)(100) + (1)(-3.162) = 10.121\) where we use the value 1 for the indicator variable USA, and 0 for the other indicator country variables.

c.) Holding the horsepower fixed, which country has the least expensive car? Why?

Holding the horsepower fixed, Japan would have the least expensive car because Japan has the lowest partial regression coefficient as shown in model 2. This means that holding the other predictor variables fixed, which is only horsepower in this case because the others are indicator variables, the slope for Japan is the most negative and has the most negative effect on price.

5.) Box-Cox Analysis

In class, we saw that a natural log transform of price was sufficient for using a linear model predicting price with age of Port wine.

wineData <- read.delim("http://statistics.uchicago.edu/~collins/data/STAT224other/wine.txt")
head(wineData)
##   vintage_yr price
## 1       1890 50.00
## 2       1900 35.00
## 3       1920 25.00
## 4       1931 11.98
## 5       1934 15.00
## 6       1935 13.00

a.) Run the Box-Cox analysis for transformation of the response variable. Obtain the suggested ?? parameter. Depending on which section of the course you are taking, the boxcox method was demonstrated in Stata or R during lecture. (In R, use the boxcox function in the MASS package. The default plot will show you the range of lambda values against the log likelihood.)

boxcox(lm(price ~ vintage_yr, data = wineData))

boxcox(lm(price ~ vintage_yr, data = wineData), lambda = seq(-0.5, 0.5, 0.1))

boxcox(lm(price ~ vintage_yr, data = wineData), lambda = seq(0, 0.3, 0.1))

We have \(\lambda = 0\) inside the interval so the transformation log(Y), or log(Price), is also suggested from the box-cox analysis. The log-likelihood is maximized when lambda = 0.24, which suggests the power transformation with lambda = 0.24.

b.) Transform Y (price) according the Box-Cox suggested transformation and perform the regression. Compare to the results for using log(price) as the response variable.

First we use age = 1972 - vintage year just like in the class example. We then transform price with the Box-Cox suggested power transformation: \(\frac{y_i^\lambda - 1}{\lambda}\) with lambda = 0.24. We then perform the regression the same way as before and also perform the regression using log(Y).

wineData <- wineData %>%
  mutate(age = 1972 - vintage_yr)
boxcoxfit <- lm((price^(0.24)-1)/(.24) ~ age, data = wineData)
logfit <- lm(log(price) ~ age, data = wineData)
summary(boxcoxfit)

To compare the models further, we plot the standardized residuals vs.the fitted values for both of the models.

wineData <- wineData %>%
  mutate(std_res = rstandard(boxcoxfit), fitted_values = fitted(boxcoxfit))

gf_point(std_res ~ fitted_values, data=wineData) %>%
  gf_labs(x = "Fitted Values (boxcox)", y = "Standardized Residuals") %>%
  gf_hline(yintercept = c(-2,0,2), linetype=2)

wineData <- wineData %>%
  mutate(std_res = rstandard(logfit), fitted_values = fitted(logfit))

gf_point(std_res ~ fitted_values, data=wineData) %>%
  gf_labs(x = "Fitted Values (log_transform)", y = "Standardized Residuals") %>%
  gf_hline(yintercept = c(-2,0,2), linetype=2)

This doesnt really show a significant difference between the log transform model and the boxcox transform model, however it seems that both models are a pretty good fit for the data.

To test whether this categorical factor adds to the price prediction, we can use an F-Test to test the following hypotheses: \(\begin{aligned}H_0: \beta_1 = \beta_2 = \beta_3 = 0 \ vs. \ H_A:\beta_i \neq 0\end{aligned}\) (for i = 1, 2, 3)

We use the anova function in R to compare the full model with the model under the null hypothesis where all the coefficients for the slops equal zero:

diamondFit_FM <- lm(price ~ x1Good + x1VeryGood + x1Excellent, data = diamondDummy)
diamondFit_RM <- lm(price ~ 1, data = diamondDummy)
anova(diamondFit_RM, diamondFit_FM)
## Analysis of Variance Table

## 2     38 138746672  3  24373666 2.2252  0.101

From the F-test, the p-value is 0.1 so we are not able to reject the null hypothesis that all the slope coefficients are zero. We conclude that the diamond cut, given as this categorical factor, is not significant and that the diamond cut does not add to the price prediction.
